    "text": {
        "title": "Unit Twenty-Three: The Present Conditional",
        "sections": [
            {
                "title": "Use of the Present Conditional",
                "paragraphs": [
                    {
                        "id": 1,
                        "content": "The **present conditional** expresses an action which depends on a **condition**, as in this English example: ‘If I could, I would go at once.’ In this example, the condition is expressed with ‘if’ (i.e., ‘on condition that’). The present conditional is often used even when the condition is not actually mentioned, as in: ‘I’m sure she would love a night out.’ Basically, the use of the Italian **present conditional** is similar to the English."
                    },
                    {
                        "content": "The **present conditional** in Italian can express **wishes or intentions**, **opinions or advice**, **requests in polite form**, **doubts**, and **conjectures**:",
                        "table": {
                            "headers": ["Italian", "English"],
                            "rows": [
                                ["**Vorrei** ballare tutta la sera.", "I would like to dance all night."],
                                ["**Mi daresti** un passaggio?", "Would you give me a lift?"],
                                ["**Fareste** meglio restare a casa.", "You’d do better to stay at home."],
                                ["**Prenderei** un caffè.", "I’d like a coffee."],
                                ["**Potreste** andare a piedi.", "You could go on foot."],
                                ["**Mi daresti** una mano?", "Would/could you give me a hand?"],
                                ["**Sapresti** fare questo lavoro?", "Would you know how to do that job?"],
                                ["**Questa potrebbe essere** la soluzione.", "This could be the solution."]
                            ]
                        }
                    }
                ]
            },
            {
                "title": "Forms of the Present Conditional",
                "paragraphs": [
                    {
                        "id": 2,
                        "content": "The **present conditional** is formed in the same way as the **future**, but with different endings:",
                        "table": {
                            "headers": ["", "Parlare (-are, To speak)", "Prendere (-ere, To take/get)", "Partire (-ire, To leave)"],
                            "rows": [
                                ["io", "parlerei", "prenderei", "partirei"],
                                ["tu", "parleresti", "prenderesti", "partiresti"],
                                ["lui/lei", "parlerebbe", "prenderebbe", "partirebbe"],
                                ["noi", "parleremmo*", "prenderemmo*", "partiremmo*"],
                                ["voi", "parlereste", "prendereste", "partireste"],
                                ["loro", "parlerebbero", "prenderebbero", "partirebbero"]
                            ]
                        }
                    },
                    {
                        "content": "* Note that the **noi** form is identical to the **future**."
                    },
                    {
                        "content": "Some verbs, such as **andare**, **avere**, **dovere**, **essere**, **fare**, **potere**, **sapere**, **stare**, **venire**, **vedere**, and **volere**, lose the vowel of their stem (e.g., **and-**, **av-**, etc.):",
                        "table": {
                            "headers": ["Andare", "Avere", "Dovere", "Essere", "Fare", "Potere", "Sapere", "Stare", "Venire", "Vedere", "Volere"],
                            "rows": [
                                ["andrei", "avrei", "dovrei", "sarei", "farei", "potrei", "saprei", "starei", "verrei", "vedrei", "vorrei"],
                                ["andresti", "avresti", "dovresti", "saresti", "faresti", "potresti", "sapresti", "staresti", "verresti", "vedresti", "vorresti"],
                                ["andrebbe", "avrebbe", "dovrebbe", "sarebbe", "farebbe", "potrebbe", "saprebbe", "starebbe", "verrebbe", "vedrebbe", "vorrebbe"],
                                ["andremmo", "avremmo", "dovremmo", "saremmo", "faremmo", "potremmo", "sapremmo", "staremmo", "verremmo", "vedremmo", "vorremmo"],
                                ["andreste", "avreste", "dovreste", "sareste", "fareste", "potreste", "sapreste", "stareste", "verreste", "vedreste", "vorreste"],
                                ["andrebbero", "avrebbero", "dovrebbero", "sarebbero", "farebbero", "potrebbero", "saprebbero", "starebbero", "verrebbero", "vedrebbero", "vorrebbero"]
                            ]
                        }
                    },
                    {
                        "content": "Examples:",
                        "table": {
                            "headers": ["Italian", "English"],
                            "rows": [
                                ["**Darei** una festa.", "I would give a party."],
                                ["**Mi faresti** un favore?", "Would you do me a favour?"],
                                ["Al posto tuo **starei** tranquillo.", "I wouldn’t worry if I were you. [lit. in your place I’d be calm]"],
                                ["Quando **andreste** in vacanza?", "When would you go on holiday?"],
                                ["Domenica **dovrei** lavorare.", "On Sunday I ought to work."],
                                ["**Potresti** aiutarmi!!", "You could help me!! [i.e., why aren’t you helping me?]"],
                                ["**Vorrei** un caffè.", "I would like a coffee."],
                                ["**Verresti** con me?", "Would you come with me?"]
                            ]
                        }
                    },
                    {
                        "content": "* The **present conditional** of **volere** is often used to express **wishes** and **requests** in a **polite form**, corresponding to the English ‘would like’."
                    }
                ]
            },
            {
                "title": "Verbs Ending in -urre",
                "paragraphs": [
                    {
                        "id": 9,
                        "content": "All verbs ending in **-urre** have the following pattern:",
                        "table": {
                            "headers": ["Produrre (To produce)", "Italian", "English"],
                            "rows": [
                                ["io", "produrrei", "I would produce"],
                                ["tu", "produrresti", "you would produce"],
                                ["lui/lei", "produrrebbe", "he/she would produce"],
                                ["noi", "produrremmo", "we would produce"],
                                ["voi", "produrreste", "you would produce"],
                                ["loro", "produrrebbero", "they would produce"]
                            ]
                        }
                    },
                    {
                        "content": "Examples:",
                        "table": {
                            "headers": ["Italian", "English"],
                            "rows": [
                                ["**Produrrei** un film se avessi i soldi.", "I would produce a film if I had the money."],
                                ["**Tradurresti** questo testo per me?", "Would you translate this text for me?"]
                            ]
                        }
                    }
                ]
            },
            {
                "title": "Negative Form",
                "paragraphs": [
                    {
                        "id": 10,
                        "content": "The **negative** is formed by putting **non** before the verb:",
                        "table": {
                            "headers": ["Italian", "English"],
                            "rows": [
                                ["**Non parlerei** con lui.", "I wouldn’t speak with him."],
                                ["**Non potreste** venire domani.", "You couldn’t come tomorrow."],
                                ["**Non vorrei** disturbarti.", "I wouldn’t want to disturb you."]
                            ]
                        }
                    }
                ]
            }
        ]
    },
